rectum","Vaginal fornices"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efundus and body of the uterus\u003C/strong\u003E are covered by peritoneum and are therefore intraperitoneal. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ebladder base\u003C/strong\u003E is retroperitoneal, with the peritoneum reflecting over only its superior surface. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervix\u003C/strong\u003E is also retroperitoneal, and the \u003Cstrong\u003Elower third of rectum\u003C/strong\u003E is completely retroperitoneal, with only the upper third being intraperitoneal. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evaginal fornices\u003C/strong\u003E are retroperitoneal structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe peritoneal reflections in the female pelvis create several important pouches: the vesicouterine pouch between bladder and uterus, and the rectouterine pouch (pouch of Douglas) between uterus and rectum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The fundus and body of the uterus are intraperitoneal structures, while the cervix, bladder, and rectum are retroperitoneal.","The peritoneum reflects over the superior surface of the bladder and posterior surface of the uterus, creating the vesicouterine pouch."],"references":["Cheng LK, O\u0027Grady G, Du P, Egbuji JU, Windsor JA, Pullan AJ. Gastrointestinal system. Wiley Interdiscip Rev Syst Biol Med. 2010 Jan-Feb;2(1):65-79. doi: 10.1002/wsbm.19. PMID: 20836011; PMCID: PMC4221587","Kahai P, Mandiga P, Wehrle CJ, Lobo S. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Large Intestine. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing, Treasure Island (FL); 2023. PMID: 29261962","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"i